{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537220"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15964"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15964"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.77,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8655"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15964"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"212"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"4981"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"7838"},{"type":"tags","id":"11623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45763"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting to participate in a clinical trial comparing two treatments for migraine prophylaxis. She has a medical history of chronic migraine and depression. Her regular medications include amitriptyline and sumatriptan. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou are designing the randomisation process for this multi-centre trial. The study coordinator suggests using sequentially numbered, opaque, sealed envelopes containing treatment allocations, stored at each participating clinic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important type of bias that this randomisation process aims to prevent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Performance bias","Detection bias","Selection bias","Attrition bias","Reporting bias"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question addresses allocation concealment in clinical trials. Allocation concealment is a critical methodological feature that prevents investigators from knowing or influencing treatment assignment before enrolling participants. The method described - sequentially numbered, opaque, sealed envelopes - is one accepted approach, though central randomisation is generally preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelection bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic differences between groups in how participants are assigned to treatments. Without proper allocation concealment, investigators might consciously or unconsciously influence which participants receive which treatment, potentially enrolling sicker patients into the treatment they believe is superior. This can significantly distort the estimated treatment effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerformance bias\u003C/strong\u003E relates to systematic differences in care provided between groups apart from the intended intervention. While important, this is primarily prevented through blinding of participants and clinicians, not through allocation concealment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetection bias\u003C/strong\u003E refers to systematic differences in how outcomes are assessed between groups. This is prevented through blinding of outcome assessors to treatment allocation, which is separate from the initial allocation process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttrition bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic differences in withdrawals between groups. This is addressed through complete follow-up and intention-to-treat analysis, rather than through the initial allocation process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReporting bias\u003C/strong\u003E refers to systematic differences between reported and unreported findings. This is prevented through pre-registration of trials and comprehensive outcome reporting, not through allocation concealment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeta-epidemiological studies have shown that trials with inadequate allocation concealment tend to overestimate treatment effects by 30% compared to trials with adequate concealment, highlighting the importance of this methodological safeguard.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Allocation concealment prevents selection bias by ensuring researchers cannot predict the next treatment assignment when enrolling participants.","Poor allocation concealment can lead to overestimation of treatment effects in clinical trials.","Sequentially numbered, opaque, sealed envelopes are one accepted method of allocation concealment in clinical trials."],"references":["Clark L, Fairhurst C, Torgerson DJ. Allocation concealment in randomised controlled trials: are we getting better? BMJ. 2016 Nov 17;355:i5663."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15964"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49378"},"attributes":